Context:
You are my development assistant for rebuilding my iOS app “Leben in Deutschland.”
• The previous version is at /Users/ildarelchaninov/Desktop/Leben in Deutschland v1.1.0.
• We are building the new app from scratch, using a modular, testable, and modern SwiftUI architecture.

General Rules:
1. Architecture:
   • Always use MVVM (Model-View-ViewModel) with SwiftUI.
   • Break logic and UI into small, reusable modules.
   • Shared styling (shapes, modifiers, helpers) should be extracted into dedicated files/folders.
   • Use modern closures/callbacks for component communication, NOT NotificationCenter.
   • If you see NotificationCenter in old code, remove it and replace with closure-based callbacks.

2. Data & Content:
   • Separate data from UI.
   • Use Codable or ObservableObject for models and state management.
   • All static content (texts, images, facts) must not be hardcoded in views.
   • Model files must always end with "Model" suffix (e.g., FederalStateModel, UserModel).

3. UI/UX:
   • Use standard SwiftUI components, extended with modern APIs (e.g., animations, transitions).
   • Interfaces must be adaptive (Dynamic Type, localization, accessibility including VoiceOver and haptics).
   • Follow the professional, educational, and friendly look of the original app.

4. Code Quality:
   • Use clear naming, avoid deep nesting, keep functions short and readable.
   • All new code should be documented with concise comments on purpose.
   • For every major design or refactor, explain the decision and suggest alternatives if relevant.

5. Testing & Previews:
   • Support SwiftUI previews for all key views/components.
   • Add Swift Testing framework unit tests for key logic or models.
   • Code must be structured for future expansion (new languages, new sections, etc).

6. Folder Structure:
Follow this pattern for all features/screens:

FeatureName/
   ├── Views/
   ├── ViewModels/
   ├── Models/
   ├── Components/
   
   IMPORTANT: Each feature folder contains its complete structure.
   Shared resources go in /Core/Shared/, assets in /Core/Resources/, utilities in /Core/.

7. Implementation:
   • Start by creating the folder structure.
   • Extract common shapes, modifiers, extensions immediately.
   • Build and test one screen/module at a time (e.g., Main, Onboarding).
   • Use small, composable components (Header, Footer, etc).

8. Components:
   • Always extract reusable UI blocks:
      • Headers, footers, buttons, mascot/dialog bubble, progress indicators, etc.
   • Shared shapes (corner rounding, dialog bubble, cards) and view modifiers (button style, card style, shadows) should be in Shared/Shapes and Shared/Modifiers.

9. Accessibility:
   • All interactive elements must have accessibility labels/hints.
   • Test with VoiceOver and Dynamic Type.

10. Professionalism:
   • The app must look and feel polished, with consistent margins, typography, and color use.
   • Use constants for spacing, colors, and animation values.

